aixm:LinguisticNote.aixm:note: Note 1: Scottish ACC is responsible for providing ATS between FL 245 and FL 660 within the Donegal Area. See ENR 2.2 Sect 1.8. Note 2: Copenhagen ACC is responsible for providing ATS between FL 195 and FL 660, within the North Sea High Area. See ENR 2.2 Sect 1.3. Note 3: Reykjavik ACC is responsible for providing ATS between SFC and FL 660, within the RATSU Triangle. See ENR 2.2 Sect 1.9. Note 4: Shannon ACC is responsible for providing ATS between FL 255 and FL 660, within the MOLAK Triangle. See ENR 2.2 Sect 1.9.3. Note 5: For sector dimensions associated with frequency allocation see UK AIP Supplement 017/2020.

Allows descent to 6000ft, keeping traffic above the lower limit of Scottish TMA 2. The southern, western and eastern boundary keep traffic at least 3NM from the ATS routes which may be used at FL100, or even lower. Note that traffic on N864 could cross the RMA.
Allows descent to 3000 ft (current MVA). Restricted to 5000 ft to keep vectoring traffic below the traffic on crossing STEPS SID.

Allows descent from the holding (at FL100) to 6000 ft, keeping traffic above the lower limit of Scottish TMA 5. The southern boundary ensures that vectoring traffic has at least 3NM separation with traffic on the GULLY SID and connecting routes.
Ensures that vectoring traffic stays above Glider area Kirknewton (SFC - 3000 ft). The western and northern boundary keep vectoring traffic at least 3NM from the SIDs and missed approach.
Allows descent to 4000 ft, keeping traffic above the lower limit of CTA 3 (3500 ft). Restricted to 6000 ft to keep vectoring traffic below the crossing traffic on STEPS SID and GLA MOODY SID.

Part of ATS Route N560 is contained within the CTA. Class E + TMZ (Transponder Mandatory Zone). Activation of the airspace will be during notified activation of EG D713/EG D713Z for Exercise Joint Warrior and other large military exercises as notified to facilitate access to the ATS Route N560. To operate UAS within this area, UAS operators are required to notify NATS via the NATS Non-Standard Flight (NSF) Portal. UAS operators are required to notify NATS at least 14 days before the date of each activity.

Allows descent to 4000 ft, keeping traffic above the lower limit of EDI CTA 4 (3500 ft). The eastern boundary keeps the vectoring traffic at least 3NM separated from the the EMBER SID (at 6000 ft) and from the section of the STRAT SID where traffic may fly below FL090. Vectoring east of this RMA is still possible if vertical separation with above mentioned SIDs is checked and maintained by the controller.

Allows descent to 2300 ft (based on current MVA). Restricted to 4000 ft to keep vectoring traffic below the crossing SIDs. The western boundary ensures that vectoring traffic has at least 3NM separation with SID traffic below 5000 ft and with glider traffic in Kirknewton glider area (SFC-3000 ft).
